0.body: An article represents a piece of content created in the content management system. Different types of content like text or video articles share the same message structure distinguished by the Article.type field. Depending on the service used to retrieve an article, this message might only contain data required on section pages (e.g. with Article.body set to null thus not containing any data that is only required on detail pages). This is sometimes referred to as Teaser . Message fields and map entries are optional unless commented otherwise. message Article {} [~] Unique ID of the article defined by the content management system (required). int64 id = 1; [~] Main content type of the article. [~] Subtype of the article. For CONTENT_TYPE_ARTICLE this field holds a sub type, for others like CONTENT_TYPE_GALLERY it may not. [~] Hierarchical section tree information of the article (required). For example: / -> /sport/ -> /sport/fussball/ [~] Generic map containing general content and configuration information of the article (required). The entry set is defined by the content management system and will vary depending on the main type of the article. For CONTENT_TYPE_ARTICLE, this map will always contain non empty values for the following keys: ref_path: URL path for this article e.g. /section/id_$ID/title.html ref_canonical: Canonical URL of this article, may differ if external, e.g. https:*www.giga.de/external.html ref_amp: AMP URL of this article headline top_line summary For CONTENT_TYPE_GALLERY, this map will always contain non empty values for the following keys: headline Clients must be resilient to unknown or missing entry sets. [~] Recursive body structure of the article to render on detail pages. This message will be empty for the teaser representation (e.g. section pages) of the article. [~] Article metadata like publication state and technical timestamps. [~] Elements of the article which are not part of the body, e.g. author information opener image/video etc. Those elements should be used to render the article as a teaser e.g. on section pages. [~] Extracted entities from the article body like people, places, organizations etc. [~] IDs of articles related to this article. Related articles are defined manually in the content management system by the editorial department. [~] Main content type of the article. [~] Not specified. [~] A text article. [~] An image article (not available as standalone article). [~] A video article. [~] A gallery article. [~] An oembed article. [~] An author article (not available as standalone article). [~] An agency article (not available as standalone article). [~] Subtype of the article. [~] Not specified. [~] Meldung/Nachricht — this is the default [~] 'Kolumne' [~] 'Bericht' [~] 'Kommentar' [~] 'Interview' [~] 'Pro und Kontra/Streitgespräch' [~] 'Reportage' [~] 'Rezension/Kritik' [~] 'Tagesanbruch' [~] 'Analyse' [~] 'Satire/Glosse' [~] Content originally imported from agency/tickers by the CMS [~] [~]
0.title: Article

1.body: Asset of an element. An asset configuration is dependant upon its use, it may alter depending on its Asset.type field.

4.body: Body of the article to render on detail pages. [~] Recursive Body nodes. [~] [~]
4.title: Body

5.body: Recursive body structure representing all types of possible body nodes inside an article. Clients must be resilient to unknown or missing nodes. [~] Type of the node (required): text p sub_headline a strong em br ul ol li img: inline image element oembed: inline oEmbed element article_sources: "Quellenapparat" article_source: A single "Quellenapparat" item containing text or a disclaimer: formatted text that holds a (health) disclaimer, e.g. used in /gesundheit/ [~] Text of the node, only set for text nodes (type == 'text'). [~] Additional information for the node depending on it's type, e.g. href for a nodes. [~] Children of the node, e.g. the text of a p. [~] Elements of the node, e.g. inline videos or galleries. [~]
5.title: BodyNode

6.body: Elements of the article which are not part of the body, e.g. author information opener image/video etc. Those elements should be used to render the article as a teaser e.g. on section pages. Different types of elements like images or videos share the same message structure distinguished by the ElementType field. [~] Type of the element. [~] The usages (relations) of an element. Example: One image element with the relations teaser and opener is used for both places. [~] Assets of the element like images, videos or metadata (required). [~] Children of the element. [~] Type of an element. [~] Not specified, not supported or yet unknown. [~] An article element. [~] An image element. // IMAGE = 2; /** A video element. [~] A gallery element. [~] An oembed element. [~] An author element. [~] An agency (e.g. DPA) element. [~] An element that represents a esi:include [~] A citation element. [~] Relation or usage of an element [~] Not specified. [~] As an opener element [~] As an teaser element [~] [~]
6.title: Element

7.body: Article metadata like publication state and technical timestamps. [~] State of the article in the content management system. [~] Manually set editorial timestamp ('Gültig von') at which the article is valid to deliver on digital platforms in seconds of UTC time since Unix epoch. [~] Manually set editorial date ('Gültig bis') till the article is valid to deliver on digital platforms in seconds of UTC time since Unix epoch. [~] Editorial date ('Publikationsdatum') of the first publication of the article in seconds of UTC time since Unix epoch. This date will be set automatically by the content management system. [~] Editorial date ('Aktualisierungsdatum') at which the article was updated in seconds of UTC time since Unix epoch. On first publication this timestamp matches publish_time. Afterwards it's either updated manually in the content management system or automatically if the article content changed significantly. [~] Technical timestamp at which the article was transformed in the API layer in seconds of UTC time since Unix epoch. [~] Number of errors occurred while fetching and/or transforming optional article components (e.g. embeds) to an article message. [~] State of the article in the content management system. [~] Not specified. [~] A published article. [~] [~]
7.title: Metadata

8.body: A Reference represents a link to another entity, for example an Article, a Section or an external website, or a whole tree structure, for example a section tree or navigation. message Reference {} [~] The type is used for filtering in a list of references. It describes a use-case, which usually has a defined render position. Example entries: unspecified stage_title stage_themenbereiche stage_header_links stage_top_themen stage_tag_category string type = 1; [~] The text or label of the reference. string label = 2; [~] The href of the reference. It can be relative or absolute. string href = 3; [~] Contains all optional attributes of the reference. target rel flag:internal layout Clients must be resilient to unknown or missing entry sets. map<string, string> fields = 4; [~] Hierarchically structured references for representing a navigation or tree. repeated Reference children = 5; [~]
8.title: Reference
